# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: stereochemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] In organic chemistry, the **Cahn–Ingold–Prelog** (**CIP**) **sequence rules** (also the **CIP priority convention**; named after Robert Sidney Cahn, Christopher Kelk Ingold, and Vladimir Prelog) are a standard process to completely and unequivocally name a stereoisomer of a molecule.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] The purpose of the CIP system is to assign an *R* or *S* descriptor to each stereocenter and an *E* or *Z* descriptor to each double bond so that the configuration of the entire molecule can be specified uniquely by including the descriptors in its systematic name.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] A molecule may contain any number of stereocenters and any number of double bonds, and each usually gives rise to two possible isomers.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] A molecule with an integer n describing the number of stereocenters will usually have 2*n* stereoisomers, and 2*n*−1 diastereomers each having an associated pair of enantiomers.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] The CIP sequence rules contribute to the precise naming of every stereoisomer of every organic molecule with all atoms of ligancy of fewer than 4 (but including ligancy of 6 as well, this term referring to the "number of neighboring atoms" bonded to a center).
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] The key article setting out the CIP sequence rules was published in 1966, and was followed by further refinements, before it was incorporated into the rules of the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC), the official body that defines organic nomenclature, in 1974.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] The rules have since been revised, most recently in 2013, as part of the IUPAC book Nomenclature of Organic Chemistry.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] A recent paper argues for changes to some of the rules (sequence rules 1b and 2) to address certain molecules for which the correct descriptors were unclear.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] However, a different problem remains: in rare cases, two different stereoisomers of the same molecule can have the same CIP descriptors, so the CIP system may not be able to unambiguously name a stereoisomer, and other systems may be preferable.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] Assignment of *R*/*S* and *E*/*Z* descriptors.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] If there is a tie, the atoms at distance 2 from the stereocenter have to be considered: a list is made for each group of further atoms bonded to the one directly attached to the stereocenter.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] Each list is arranged in order of decreasing atomic number Z.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] Then the lists are compared atom by atom; at the earliest difference, the group containing the atom of higher atomic number Z receives higher priority.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] If there is still a tie, each atom in each of the two lists is replaced with a sublist of the other atoms bonded to it (at distance 3 from the stereocenter), the sublists are arranged in decreasing order of atomic number Z, and the entire structure is again compared atom by atom.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] This process is repeated recursively, each time with atoms one bond farther from the stereocenter, until the tie is broken.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] If two groups differ only in isotopes, then the larger atomic mass is used to set the priority.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] If an atom, A, is double-bonded to another atom, then atom A should be treated as though it is "connected to the same atom twice".
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] An atom that is double-bonded has a higher priority than an atom that is single bonded.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] When dealing with double bonded priority groups, one is allowed to visit the same atom twice as one creates an arc.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] When B is replaced with a list of attached atoms, A itself, but not its "phantom", is excluded in accordance with the general principle of not doubling back along a bond that has just been followed.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] A triple bond is handled the same way except that A and B are each connected to two phantom atoms of the other.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] If two substituents on an atom are geometric isomers of each other, the *Z*-isomer has higher priority than the *E*-isomer.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] To handle a molecule containing one or more cycles, one must first expand it into a tree (called a **hierarchical digraph**) by traversing bonds in all possible paths starting at the stereocenter.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] When the traversal encounters an atom through which the current path has already passed, a phantom atom is generated in order to keep the tree finite.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] A single atom of the original molecule may appear in many places (some as phantoms, some not) in the tree.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] A chiral sp3 hybridized isomer contains four different substituents.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] All four substituents are assigned priorities based on its atomic numbers.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] After the substituents of a stereocenter have been assigned their priorities, the molecule is oriented in space so that the group with the lowest priority is pointed away from the observer.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] If the substituents are numbered from 1 (highest priority) to 4 (lowest priority), then the sense of rotation of a curve passing through 1, 2 and 3 distinguishes the stereoisomers.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] In a configurational isomer, the lowest priority group (most times hydrogen) is positioned behind the plane or the hatched bond going away from the reader.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] The highest priority group will have an arc drawn connecting to the rest of the groups, finishing at the group of third priority.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] An arc drawn clockwise, has the *rectus* (*R*) assignment.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] An arc drawn counterclockwise, has the *sinister* (*S*) assignment.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] The names are derived from the Latin for 'right' and 'left', respectively.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] When naming an organic isomer, the abbreviation for either rectus or sinister assignment is placed in front of the name in parentheses.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] For example, 3-methyl-1-pentene with a rectus assignment is formatted as (*R*)-3-methyl-1-pentene.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] A practical method of determining whether an enantiomer is *R* or *S* is by using the right-hand rule: one wraps the molecule with the fingers in the direction 1 → 2 → 3.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] If the thumb points in the direction of the fourth substituent, the enantiomer is *R*; otherwise, it is *S*.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] It is possible in rare cases that two substituents on an atom differ only in their absolute configuration (*R* or *S*).
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] If the relative priorities of these substituents need to be established, *R* takes priority over *S*.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] When this happens, the descriptor of the stereocenter is a lowercase letter (*r* or *s*) instead of the uppercase letter normally used.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] For double bonded molecules, Cahn–Ingold–Prelog priority rules (CIP rules) are followed to determine the priority of substituents of the double bond.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] If both of the high priority groups are on the same side of the double bond (*cis* configuration), then the stereoisomer is assigned the configuration *Z* (*zusammen,* German word meaning "together").
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] In some cases where stereogenic centers are formed, the configuration must be specified.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] Without the presence of a non-covalent interaction, a compound is achiral.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] Some professionals have proposed a new rule to account for this.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] This rule states that "non-covalent interactions have a fictitious number between 0 and 1" when assigning priority.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] Compounds in which this occurs are referred to as coordination compounds.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] The spiro carbon, C, is a stereogenic centre, and priority can be assigned a>a′>b>b′, in which one ring (both give the same answer) contains atoms a and b adjacent to the spiro carbon, and the other contains a′ and b′.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] The configuration at C may then be assigned as for any other stereocentre.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] The following are examples of application of the nomenclature.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] If a compound has more than one chiral stereocenter, each center is denoted by either *R* or *S*.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] For example, ephedrine exists in (1*R*,2*S*) and (1*S*,2*R*) stereoisomers, which are distinct mirror-image forms of each other, making them enantiomers.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] This compound also exists as the two enantiomers written (1*R*,2*R*) and (1*S*,2*S*), which are named pseudoephedrine rather than ephedrine.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] All four of these isomers are named 2-methylamino-1-phenyl-1-propanol in systematic nomenclature.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] However, ephedrine and pseudoephedrine are diastereomers, or stereoisomers that are not enantiomers because they are not related as mirror-image copies.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] Pseudoephedrine and ephedrine are given different names because, as diastereomers, they have different chemical properties, even for racemic mixtures of each.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] More generally, for any pair of enantiomers, all of the descriptors are opposite: (*R*,*R*) and (*S*,*S*) are enantiomers, as are (*R*,*S*) and (*S*,*R*).
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] Diastereomers have at least one descriptor in common; for example (*R*,*S*) and (*R*,*R*) are diastereomers, as are (*S*,*R*) and (*S*,*S*).
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] This holds true also for compounds having more than two stereocenters: if two stereoisomers have at least one descriptor in common, they are diastereomers.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] If all the descriptors are opposite, they are enantiomers.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] A meso compound is an achiral molecule, despite having two or more stereogenic centers.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] A meso compound is superposable on its mirror image, therefore it reduces the number of stereoisomers predicted by the 2n rule.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] This occurs because the molecule obtains a plane of symmetry that causes the molecule to rotate around the central carbon–carbon bond.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] One example is meso-tartaric acid, in which (*R*,*S*) is the same as the (*S*,*R*) form.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] In meso compounds the *R* and *S* stereocenters occur in symmetrically positioned pairs.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] The relative configuration of two stereoisomers may be denoted by the descriptors *R* and *S* with an asterisk (*).
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] To begin, the lowest-numbered (according to IUPAC systematic numbering) stereogenic center is given the *R** descriptor.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] To designate two anomers the relative stereodescriptors alpha (α) and beta (β) are used.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] In the α anomer the *anomeric carbon atom* and the *reference atom* do have opposite configurations (*R*,*S*) or (*S*,*R*), whereas in the β anomer they are the same (*R*,*R*) or (*S*,*S*).
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] Stereochemistry also plays a role assigning *faces* to trigonal molecules such as ketones.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] A nucleophile in a nucleophilic addition can approach the carbonyl group from two opposite sides or faces.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] When an achiral nucleophile attacks acetone, both faces are identical and there is only one reaction product.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] When the nucleophile attacks butanone, the faces are not identical (*enantiotopic*) and a racemic product results.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] When the nucleophile is a chiral molecule diastereoisomers are formed.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] When one face of a molecule is shielded by substituents or geometric constraints compared to the other face the faces are called diastereotopic.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] The same rules that determine the stereochemistry of a stereocenter (*R* or *S*) also apply when assigning the face of a molecular group.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] The faces are then called the ***Re*-face** and ***Si*-face**.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] In the example displayed on the right, the compound acetophenone is viewed from the *Re*-face.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] Hydride addition as in a reduction process from this side will form the (*S*)-enantiomer and attack from the opposite *Si*-face will give the (*R*)-enantiomer.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] However, adding a chemical group to the prochiral center from the *Re*-face will not always lead to an (*S*)-stereocenter, as the priority of the chemical group has to be taken into account.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] That is, the absolute stereochemistry of the product is determined on its own and not by considering which face it was attacked from.
[src:stereochemistry/cahn-ingold-prelog-priority-rules] In the above-mentioned example, if chloride (*Z* = 17) were added to the prochiral center from the *Re*-face, this would result in an (*R*)-enantiomer.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] In chemistry, a molecule or ion is called **chiral** (/ˈkaɪrəl/) if it cannot be superposed on its mirror image by any combination of rotations, translations, and some conformational changes.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] This geometric property is called **chirality** (/kaɪˈrælɪti/).
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The terms are derived from Ancient Greek χείρ (*cheir*) 'hand'; which is the canonical example of an object with this property.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] A chiral molecule or ion exists in two stereoisomers that are mirror images of each other, called enantiomers; they are often distinguished as either "right-handed" or "left-handed" by their absolute configuration or some other criterion.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The two enantiomers have the same chemical properties, except when reacting with other chiral compounds.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] They also have the same physical properties, except that they often have opposite optical activities.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] A homogeneous mixture of the two enantiomers in equal parts, a racemic mixture, differs chemically and physically from the pure enantiomers.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Chiral molecules will usually have a stereogenic element from which chirality arises.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The most common type of stereogenic element is a stereogenic center, or stereocenter.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] In the case of organic compounds, stereocenters most frequently take the form of a carbon atom with four distinct groups attached to it in a tetrahedral geometry.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Less commonly, other atoms like N, P, S, and Si can also serve as stereocenters, provided they have four distinct substituents (including lone pair electrons) attached to them.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] A given stereocenter has two possible configurations (R and S), which give rise to stereoisomers (diastereomers and enantiomers) in molecules with one or more stereocenter.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] For a chiral molecule with one or more stereocenter, the enantiomer corresponds to the stereoisomer in which every stereocenter has the opposite configuration.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] An organic compound with only one stereogenic carbon is always chiral.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] On the other hand, an organic compound with multiple stereogenic carbons is typically, but not always, chiral.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] In particular, if the stereocenters are configured in such a way that the molecule can take a conformation having a plane of symmetry or an inversion point, then the molecule is achiral and is known as a *meso* compound.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Molecules with chirality arising from one or more stereocenters are classified as possessing central chirality.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] There are two other types of stereogenic elements that can give rise to chirality, a stereogenic axis (axial chirality) and a stereogenic plane (planar chirality).
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Finally, the inherent curvature of a molecule can also give rise to chirality (inherent chirality).
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] These types of chirality are far less common than central chirality.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] BINOL is a typical example of an axially chiral molecule, while *trans*-cyclooctene is a commonly cited example of a planar chiral molecule.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Finally, helicene possesses helical chirality, which is one type of inherent chirality.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Chirality is an important concept for stereochemistry and biochemistry.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Most substances relevant to biology are chiral, such as carbohydrates (sugars, starch, and cellulose), all but one of the amino acids that are the building blocks of proteins, and the nucleic acids.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Naturally occurring triglycerides are often chiral, but not always.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] In living organisms, one typically finds only one of the two enantiomers of a chiral compound.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] For that reason, organisms that consume a chiral compound usually can metabolize only one of its enantiomers.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] For the same reason, the potencies or effects of enantiomers of a pharmaceutical can differ sharply.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The chirality of a molecule is based on the molecular symmetry of its conformations.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] A conformation of a molecule is chiral if and only if it belongs to the *Cn*, *Dn*, *T*, *O*, or *I* point groups (the chiral point groups).
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] For example, despite having chiral *gauche* conformers that belong to the *C*2 point group, butane is considered achiral at room temperature because rotation about the central C–C bond rapidly interconverts the enantiomers (3.4 kcal/mol barrier).
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Similarly, *cis*-1,2-dichlorocyclohexane consists of chair conformers that are nonidentical mirror images, but the two can interconvert via the cyclohexane chair flip (~10 kcal/mol barrier).
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] As another example, amines with three distinct substituents (R1R2R3N:) are also regarded as achiral molecules because their enantiomeric pyramidal conformers rapidly undergo pyramidal inversion.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] However, if the temperature in question is low enough, the process that interconverts the enantiomeric chiral conformations becomes slow compared to a given timescale.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The molecule would then be considered to be chiral at that temperature.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The relevant timescale is, to some degree, arbitrarily defined: 1000 seconds is sometimes employed, as this is regarded as the lower limit for the amount of time required for chemical or chromatographic separation of enantiomers in a practical sense.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Molecules that are chiral at room temperature due to restricted rotation about a single bond (barrier to rotation ≥ ca.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] 23 kcal/mol) are said to exhibit atropisomerism.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] A chiral compound can contain no improper axis of rotation (*Sn*), which includes planes of symmetry and inversion center.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Chiral molecules are always dissymmetric (lacking *Sn*) but not always asymmetric (lacking all symmetry elements except the trivial identity).
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The following table shows some examples of chiral and achiral molecules, with the Schoenflies notation of the point group of the molecule.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] In the achiral molecules, X and Y (with no subscript) represent achiral groups, whereas XR and XS or YR and YS represent enantiomers.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Note that there is no meaning to the orientation of an *S*2 axis, which is just an inversion.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Any orientation will do, so long as it passes through the center of inversion.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Also note that higher symmetries of chiral and achiral molecules also exist, and symmetries that do not include those in the table, such as the chiral *C*3 or the achiral *S*4.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] An example of a molecule that does not have a mirror plane or an inversion and yet would be considered achiral is 1,1-difluoro-2,2-dichlorocyclohexane (or 1,1-difluoro-3,3-dichlorocyclohexane).
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] This may exist in many conformers (conformational isomers), but none of them has a mirror plane.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] In order to have a mirror plane, the cyclohexane ring would have to be flat, widening the bond angles and giving the conformation a very high energy.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] This compound would not be considered chiral because the chiral conformers interconvert easily.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] A *stereogenic center* (or *stereocenter*) is an atom such that swapping the positions of two ligands (connected groups) on that atom results in a molecule that is stereoisomeric to the original.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] For example, a common case is a tetrahedral carbon bonded to four distinct groups **a**, **b**, **c**, and **d** (C**abcd**), where swapping any two groups (e.g., C**bacd**) leads to a stereoisomer of the original, so the central C is a stereocenter.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Many chiral molecules have point chirality, namely a single chiral stereogenic center that coincides with an atom.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] This stereogenic center usually has four or more bonds to different groups and may be carbon (as in many biological molecules), phosphorus (as in many organophosphates), silicon, or a metal (as in many chiral coordination compounds).
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] However, a stereogenic center can also be a trivalent atom whose bonds are not in the same plane, such as phosphorus in P-chiral phosphines (PRR′R″) and sulfur in S-chiral sulfoxides (OSRR′), because a lone-pair of electrons is present instead of a fourth bond.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Similarly, a stereogenic axis (or plane) is defined as an axis (or plane) in the molecule such that the swapping of any two ligands attached to the axis (or plane) gives rise to a stereoisomer.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] For instance, the C2-symmetric species 1,1′-bi-2-naphthol (BINOL) and 1,3-dichloroallene have stereogenic axes and exhibit axial chirality, while (*E*)-cyclooctene and many ferrocene derivatives bearing two or more substituents have stereogenic planes and exhibit planar chirality.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Chirality can also arise from isotopic differences between substituents, such as in the deuterated benzyl alcohol PhCHDOH; which is chiral and optically active ([*α*]D = 0.715°), even though the non-deuterated compound PhCH2OH is not.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] If two enantiomers easily interconvert, the pure enantiomers may be practically impossible to separate, and only the racemic mixture is observable.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] This is the case, for example, of most amines with three different substituents (NRR′R″), because of the low energy barrier for nitrogen inversion.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] When the optical rotation for an enantiomer is too low for practical measurement, the species is said to exhibit cryptochirality.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Chirality is an intrinsic part of the identity of a molecule, so the systematic name includes details of the absolute configuration (*R/S*, *D/L*, or other designations).
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Many biologically active molecules are chiral, including the naturally occurring amino acids (the building blocks of proteins) and sugars.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The origin of this homochirality in biology is the subject of much debate.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Most scientists believe that Earth life's "choice" of chirality was purely random, and that if carbon-based life forms exist elsewhere in the universe, their chemistry could theoretically have opposite chirality.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] However, there is some suggestion that early amino acids could have formed in comet dust.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] In this case, circularly polarised radiation (which makes up 17% of stellar radiation) could have caused the selective destruction of one chirality of amino acids, leading to a selection bias which ultimately resulted in all life on Earth being homochiral.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Enzymes, which are chiral, often distinguish between the two enantiomers of a chiral substrate.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] One could imagine an enzyme as having a glove-like cavity that binds a substrate.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] If this glove is right-handed, then one enantiomer will fit inside and be bound, whereas the other enantiomer will have a poor fit and is unlikely to bind.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] L-forms of amino acids tend to be tasteless, whereas D-forms tend to taste sweet.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Spearmint leaves contain the L-enantiomer of the chemical carvone or *R*-(−)-carvone and caraway seeds contain the D-enantiomer or *S*-(+)-carvone.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The two smell different to most people because our olfactory receptors are chiral.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Chirality is important in context of ordered phases as well, for example the addition of a small amount of an optically active molecule to a nematic phase (a phase that has long range orientational order of molecules) transforms that phase to a chiral nematic phase (or cholesteric phase).
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Chirality in context of such phases in polymeric fluids has also been studied in this context.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Chirality is a symmetry property, not a property of any part of the periodic table.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Thus many inorganic materials, molecules, and ions are chiral.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Quartz is an example from the mineral kingdom.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Such noncentric materials are of interest for applications in nonlinear optics.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] In the areas of coordination chemistry and organometallic chemistry, chirality is pervasive and of practical importance.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] A famous example is tris(bipyridine)ruthenium(II) complex in which the three bipyridine ligands adopt a chiral propeller-like arrangement.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Chiral ligands confer chirality to a metal complex, as illustrated by metal-amino acid complexes.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] If the metal exhibits catalytic properties, its combination with a chiral ligand is the basis of asymmetric catalysis.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The term *optical activity* is derived from the interaction of chiral materials with polarized light.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] In a solution, the (−)-form, or levorotatory form, of an optical isomer rotates the plane of a beam of linearly polarized light counterclockwise.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The (+)-form, or dextrorotatory form, of an optical isomer does the opposite.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The rotation of light is measured using a polarimeter and is expressed as the optical rotation.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Enantiomers can be separated by chiral resolution.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] This often involves forming crystals of a salt composed of one of the enantiomers and an acid or base from the so-called chiral pool of naturally occurring chiral compounds, such as malic acid or the amine brucine.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Some racemic mixtures spontaneously crystallize into right-handed and left-handed crystals that can be separated by hand.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Louis Pasteur used this method to separate left-handed and right-handed sodium ammonium tartrate crystals in 1849.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Sometimes it is possible to seed a racemic solution with a right-handed and a left-handed crystal so that each will grow into a large crystal.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Liquid chromatography (HPLC and TLC) may also be used as an analytical method for the direct separation of enantiomers and the control of enantiomeric purity, e.g. active pharmaceutical ingredients (APIs) which are chiral.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The prediction of chiral properties using computational methods has emerged as an important area in modern stereochemistry, complementing experimental techniques for characterizing and separating enantiomers.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] These approaches leverage machine learning algorithms and molecular representations to predict various chiral-specific behaviors, including chromatographic retention, optical rotation, and stereochemical assignments.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Computational methods for representing molecular chirality must encode three-dimensional stereochemical information in a format suitable for machine learning algorithms.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Traditional molecular descriptors used in computational chemistry, such as circular fingerprints (Extended Connectivity Fingerprints or ECFP), can encode structural information including stereochemical features.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] These descriptors represent molecules as fixed-length binary vectors that capture local atomic environments and connectivity patterns.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] However, conventional fingerprints may not optimally capture the subtle three-dimensional differences between enantiomers.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Neural network-based molecular representations can be derived from SMILES strings.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Variational autoencoders and heteroencoders trained on large databases of molecular structures can generate latent space vectors (LSVs) that encode molecular properties in a continuous, lower-dimensional space.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] These methods calculate difference vectors between the descriptor of a molecule and that of its enantiomer, or between the original descriptor and one derived from a stereochemistry-depleted SMILES string.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Such difference descriptors can amplify the stereochemical information relevant to chiral properties while reducing noise from other structural features.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Machine learning models trained on these molecular representations have been applied to predict various chirality-related properties.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] One practical application is forecasting the elution order of enantiomers in chiral chromatography.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Models trained on experimental retention data from chiral stationary phases can learn structure-retention relationships.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Random Forest and other ensemble methods have been applied to predict which enantiomer elutes first on columns such as Chiralpak AD-H using both traditional circular fingerprints and neural network-derived descriptors.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Another application is the prediction of optical rotation, a fundamental chiral property.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Machine learning models have been developed to predict specific rotation values for chiral molecules based on their structure, with applications to both organic compounds and specialized classes such as chiral fluorinated molecules.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] These predictions can assist in structural characterization and quality control in pharmaceutical development.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] While these machine learning approaches show promise, several limitations remain.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Model accuracy depends heavily on training data quality and coverage of chemical space.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Neural network architectures, particularly Transformers, face inherent challenges in learning stereochemical features from string-based representations like SMILES.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] These models tend to recognize partial molecular structures early in training but require significantly longer to accurately distinguish between enantiomers, sometimes exhibiting periods of confusion where @ and @@ tokens are frequently interchanged.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The interpretability of neural network-based descriptors is often limited compared to traditional physically-motivated descriptors.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Additionally, these methods typically perform best for compounds structurally similar to training data and may not generalize well to novel scaffolds or unusual stereochemical arrangements.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The rotation of plane polarized light by chiral substances was first observed by Jean-Baptiste Biot in 1812, and gained considerable importance in the sugar industry, analytical chemistry, and pharmaceuticals.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Louis Pasteur deduced in 1848 that this phenomenon has a molecular basis.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] The term *chirality* itself was coined by Lord Kelvin in 1894.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] Individual enantiomers or diastereomers of a compound were formerly called **optical isomers** due to their distinct optical properties.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] At one time, chirality was thought to be restricted to organic chemistry, but this misconception was overthrown by the resolution of a purely inorganic compound, a cobalt complex called hexol, by Alfred Werner in 1911.
[src:stereochemistry/chirality-chemistry] In the early 1970s, various groups established that the human olfactory organ is capable of distinguishing chiral compounds.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] In chemistry, **rotamers** are chemical species that differ from one another primarily due to rotations about one single bond.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Various arrangements of atoms in a molecule that differ by rotation about single bonds can also be referred to as **conformations**.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Conformations, which represent local minima on the potential energy surface, are called **conformers**.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Conformers can differ from one another due to rotation of multiple bonds; rotamers are a subset of conformers.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Conformers/rotamers usually differ little in their energies, so they are almost never separable in a practical sense.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Rotations about single bonds are subject to small energy barriers.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] When the time scale for interconversion is long enough for isolation of individual rotamers (usually arbitrarily defined as a half-life of interconversion of 1000 seconds or longer), the species are termed atropisomers.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The ring-flip of substituted cyclohexanes constitutes a common form of conformers.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The study of the energetics of bond rotation is referred to as **conformational analysis**.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] In some cases, conformational analysis can be used to predict and explain product selectivity, mechanisms, and rates of reactions.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Conformational analysis also plays an important role in rational, structure-based drug design.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Rotating their carbon–carbon bonds, the molecules ethane and propane have three local energy minima.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] They are structurally and energetically equivalent, and are called the *staggered conformers*.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] For each molecule, the three substituents emanating from each carbon–carbon bond are staggered, with each H–C–C–H dihedral angle (and H–C–C–CH3 dihedral angle in the case of propane) equal to 60° (or approximately equal to 60° in the case of propane).
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The three eclipsed conformations, in which the dihedral angles are zero, are transition states (energy maxima) connecting two equivalent energy minima, the staggered conformers.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The butane molecule is the simplest molecule for which single bond rotations result in two types of nonequivalent structures, known as the *anti*- and *gauche-*conformers (see figure).
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The energy separation between gauche and anti is 0.9 kcal/mol associated with the strain energy of the gauche conformer.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The anti conformer is, therefore, the most stable (≈ 0 kcal/mol).
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The three eclipsed conformations with dihedral angles of 0°, 120°, and 240° are transition states between conformers.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Note that the two eclipsed conformations have distinct energies: at 0° the two methyl groups are eclipsed, resulting in higher energy (≈ 5 kcal/mol) than at 120°, where the methyl groups are eclipsed with hydrogens (≈ 3.5 kcal/mol).
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] A rough approximate function can illustrate the main features of the conformational analysis for unbranched linear alkanes with rotation around a central C–C bond (C1–C2 in ethane, C2–C3 in butane, C3–C4 in hexane, etc.).
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The members of this series have the general formula C*2n*H*4n+2* with the index *n = 1, 2, 3,* etc.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] It can be assumed that the angle strain is negligible in alkanes since the bond angles are all near the tetrahedral ideal.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The energy profile is thus periodic with $2\pi /3$ (120°) periodicity due to the threefold symmetry of sp3-hybridized carbon atoms.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] For alkanes, the dominant term is usually $k=3$ , reflecting the threefold rotational symmetry.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Higher terms may be included for precision where steric effects vary.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The primary contribution comes from torsional strain due to alkyl groups eclipsing, captured by the $\cos(3\theta )$ term.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Steric interactions rise with the size of substituents (H– for ethane, CH3– for butane, C2H5– for hexane, etc.), taken into account by the $\cos(\theta )$ term $(k=1)$ .
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The number of carbon atoms clearly influences the size of substituents on the central C–C bond.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] In general, for unbranched linear alkanes with even-numbered chains, there will be two C*n-1*H*2n-1* group substituents.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Here $V(\theta ,n)$ is given in kcal/mol and $k=1,3$ .
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] This function largely neglects angle strain and long-range interactions for the n members of the series.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] While simple molecules can be described by these types of conformations, more complex molecules require the use of the Klyne–Prelog system to describe the conformers.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Three isotherms are given in the diagram depicting the equilibrium distribution of two conformers at various temperatures.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] At a free energy difference of 0 kcal/mol, this analysis gives an equilibrium constant of 1, meaning that two conformers exist in a 1:1 ratio.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The two have equal free energy; neither is more stable, so neither predominates compared to the other.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] A negative difference in free energy means that a conformer interconverts to a thermodynamically more stable conformation, thus the equilibrium constant will always be greater than 1.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] For example, the Δ*G°* for the transformation of butane from the *gauche* conformer to the *anti* conformer is −0.47 kcal/mol at 298 K.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] This gives an equilibrium constant is about 2.2 in favor of the *anti* conformer, or a 31:69 mixture of *gauche*:*anti* conformers at equilibrium.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Conversely, a positive difference in free energy means the conformer already is the more stable one, so the interconversion is an unfavorable equilibrium (*K* < 1).
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The left hand side is the proportion of conformer *i* in an equilibrating mixture of *M* conformers in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] On the right side, *E**k* (*k* = 1, 2, ..., *M*) is the energy of conformer *k*, *R* is the molar ideal gas constant (approximately equal to 8.314 J/(mol·K) or 1.987 cal/(mol·K)), and *T* is the absolute temperature.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The denominator of the right side is the partition function.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The effects of electrostatic and steric interactions of the substituents as well as orbital interactions such as hyperconjugation are responsible for the relative stability of conformers and their transition states.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The contributions of these factors vary depending on the nature of the substituents and may either contribute positively or negatively to the energy barrier.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Computational studies of small molecules such as ethane suggest that electrostatic effects make the greatest contribution to the energy barrier; however, the barrier is traditionally attributed primarily to steric interactions.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] In the case of cyclic systems, the steric effect and contribution to the free energy can be approximated by A values, which measure the energy difference when a substituent on cyclohexane in the axial as compared to the equatorial position.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] In large (>14 atom) rings, there are many accessible low-energy conformations which correspond to the strain-free diamond lattice.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The short timescale of interconversion precludes the separation of conformer in most cases.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Atropisomers are conformational isomers which can be separated due to restricted rotation.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The equilibrium between conformational isomers can be observed using a variety of spectroscopic techniques.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Protein folding also generates conformers which can be observed.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The Karplus equation relates the dihedral angle of vicinal protons to their J-coupling constants as measured by NMR.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The equation aids in the elucidation of protein folding as well as the conformations of other rigid aliphatic molecules.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Protein side chains exhibit rotamers, whose distribution is determined by their steric interaction with different conformations of the backbone.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] This effect is evident from statistical analysis of the conformations of protein side chains in the Backbone-dependent rotamer library.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Conformational dynamics can be monitored by variable temperature NMR spectroscopy.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The technique applies to barriers of 8–14 kcal/mol, and species exhibiting such dynamics are often called "fluxional".
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] For example, in cyclohexane derivatives, the two chair conformers interconvert rapidly at room temperature.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The ring-flip proceeds at a rates of approximately 105 ring-flips/sec, with an overall energy barrier of 10 kcal/mol (42 kJ/mol).
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] This barrier precludes separation at ambient temperatures.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] However, at low temperatures below the coalescence point one can directly monitor the equilibrium by NMR spectroscopy and by dynamic, temperature dependent NMR spectroscopy the barrier interconversion.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Besides NMR spectroscopy, IR spectroscopy is used to measure conformer ratios.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] For the axial and equatorial conformer of bromocyclohexane, νCBr differs by almost 50 cm−1.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Reaction rates are highly dependent on the conformation of the reactants.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] In many cases the dominant product arises from the reaction of the *less prevalent* conformer, by virtue of the Curtin-Hammett principle.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] This is typical for situations where the conformational equilibration is much faster than reaction to form the product.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The dependence of a reaction on the stereochemical orientation is therefore usually only visible in configurational analysis, in which a particular conformation is locked by substituents.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Prediction of rates of many reactions involving the transition between sp2 and sp3 states, such as ketone reduction, alcohol oxidation or nucleophilic substitution is possible if all conformers and their relative stability ruled by their strain is taken into account.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] One example where the rotamers become significant is elimination reactions, which involve the simultaneous removal of a proton and a leaving group from vicinal or *anti*periplanar positions under the influence of a base.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The mechanism requires that the departing atoms or groups follow antiparallel trajectories.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] For open chain substrates this geometric prerequisite is met by at least one of the three staggered conformers.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] For some cyclic substrates such as cyclohexane, however, an antiparallel arrangement may not be attainable depending on the substituents which might set a conformational lock.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Adjacent substituents on a cyclohexane ring can achieve antiperiplanarity only when they occupy trans diaxial positions (that is, both are in axial position, one going up and one going down).
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The thermodynamically unfavored conformation has the *t*-Bu group in the axial position, which is higher in energy by more than 5 kcal/mol (see A value).
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] As a result, the *t*-Bu group "locks" the ring in the conformation where it is in the equatorial position and substitution reaction is observed.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] On the other hand, *cis*-4-*tert*-butylcyclohexyl chloride undergoes elimination because antiperiplanarity of Cl and H can be achieved when the *t*-Bu group is in the favorable equatorial position.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] isomer can attain antiperiplanarity only via the unfavored axial conformer; therefore, it does not eliminate.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] isomer is already in the correct geometry in its most stable conformation; therefore, it eliminates easily.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The repulsion between an axial *t*-butyl group and hydrogen atoms in the 1,3-diaxial position is so strong that the cyclohexane ring will revert to a twisted boat conformation.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The strain in cyclic structures is usually characterized by deviations from ideal bond angles (Baeyer strain), ideal torsional angles (Pitzer strain) or transannular (Prelog) interactions.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Alkane conformers arise from rotation around sp3 hybridised carbon–carbon sigma bonds.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The smallest alkane with such a chemical bond, ethane, exists as an infinite number of conformations with respect to rotation around the C–C bond.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Two of these are recognised as energy minimum (staggered conformation) and energy maximum (eclipsed conformation) forms.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The existence of specific conformations is due to hindered rotation around sigma bonds, although a role for hyperconjugation is proposed by a competing theory.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The importance of energy minima and energy maxima is seen by extension of these concepts to more complex molecules for which stable conformations may be predicted as minimum-energy forms.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The determination of stable conformations has also played a large role in the establishment of the concept of asymmetric induction and the ability to predict the stereochemistry of reactions controlled by steric effects.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] In the example of staggered ethane in Newman projection, a hydrogen atom on one carbon atom has a 60° **torsional angle** or **torsion angle** with respect to the nearest hydrogen atom on the other carbon so that steric hindrance is minimised.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The staggered conformation is more stable by 12.5 kJ/mol than the eclipsed conformation, which is the energy maximum for ethane.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] In the eclipsed conformation the torsional angle is minimised.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] In butane, the two staggered conformations are no longer equivalent and represent two distinct conformers:the **anti-conformation** (left-most, below) and the **gauche conformation** (right-most, below).
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Both conformations are free of torsional strain, but, in the gauche conformation, the two methyl groups are in closer proximity than the sum of their van der Waals radii.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The interaction between the two methyl groups is repulsive (van der Waals strain), and an energy barrier results.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The eclipsed methyl groups exert a greater steric strain because of their greater electron density compared to lone hydrogen atoms.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The textbook explanation for the existence of the energy maximum for an eclipsed conformation in ethane is steric hindrance, but, with a C-C bond length of 154 pm and a Van der Waals radius for hydrogen of 120 pm, the hydrogen atoms in ethane are never in each other's way.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The question of whether steric hindrance is responsible for the eclipsed energy maximum is a topic of debate to this day.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] One alternative to the steric hindrance explanation is based on hyperconjugation as analyzed within the Natural Bond Orbital framework.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] In the staggered conformation, one C-H sigma bonding orbital donates electron density to the antibonding orbital of the other C-H bond.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] The energetic stabilization of this effect is maximized when the two orbitals have maximal overlap, occurring in the staggered conformation.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] There is no overlap in the eclipsed conformation, leading to a disfavored energy maximum.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] On the other hand, an analysis within quantitative molecular orbital theory shows that 2-orbital-4-electron (steric) repulsions are dominant over hyperconjugation.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] A valence bond theory study also emphasizes the importance of steric effects.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Torsional strain or "Pitzer strain" refers to resistance to twisting about a bond.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] In *n*-pentane, the terminal methyl groups experience additional pentane interference.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Replacing hydrogen by fluorine in polytetrafluoroethylene changes the stereochemistry from the zigzag geometry to that of a helix due to electrostatic repulsion of the fluorine atoms in the 1,3 positions.
[src:stereochemistry/conformational-isomerism] Evidence for the helix structure in the crystalline state is derived from X-ray crystallography and from NMR spectroscopy and circular dichroism in solution.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] In stereochemistry, **diastereomers** (sometimes called **diastereoisomers**) are a type of stereoisomer.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Diastereomers are defined as non-mirror image, non-identical stereoisomers.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Hence, they occur when two or more stereoisomers of a compound have different configurations at one or more (but not all) of the equivalent (related) stereocenters and are not mirror images of each other.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] When two diastereoisomers differ from each other at only one stereocenter, they are epimers.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Each stereocenter gives rise to two different configurations and thus typically increases the number of stereoisomers by a factor of two.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Diastereomers differ from enantiomers in that the latter are pairs of stereoisomers that differ in all stereocenters and are therefore mirror images of one another.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Enantiomers of a compound with more than one stereocenter are also diastereomers of the other stereoisomers of that compound that are not their mirror image (that is, excluding the opposing enantiomer).
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Diastereomers have different physical properties (unlike most aspects of enantiomers) and often different chemical reactivity.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Diastereomers differ not only in physical properties but also in chemical reactivity — how a compound reacts with others.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Glucose and galactose, for instance, are diastereomers.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Even though they share the same molar weight, glucose is more stable than galactose.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] This difference in stability causes galactose to be absorbed slightly faster than glucose in the human body.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] When the single bond between the two centres is free to rotate, cis/trans descriptors become invalid.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Two widely accepted prefixes used to distinguish diastereomers on sp³-hybridised bonds in an open-chain molecule are **syn** and **anti**.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Masamune proposed the descriptors which work even if the groups are not attached to adjacent carbon atoms.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] It also works regardless of CIP priorities.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Syn describes groups on the same face while anti describes groups on opposite faces.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] The concept applies only to the Zigzag projection.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] The descriptors only describe relative stereochemistry rather than absolute stereochemistry.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Two older prefixes still commonly used to distinguish diastereomers are **threo** and **erythro**.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] In the case of saccharides, when drawn in the Fischer projection the erythro isomer has two identical substituents on the same side and the threo isomer has them on opposite sides.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] When drawn as a zig-zag chain, the erythro isomer has two identical substituents on different sides of the plane (anti).
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] The names are derived from the diastereomeric four-carbon aldoses erythrose and threose.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] These prefixes are not recommended for general use because it is often difficult to discern how to apply their definitions to particular compounds.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Threitol and erythritol are both four-carbon sugar alcohols.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Erythritol is achiral (has at least one conformation with a plane or center of symmetry), whereas threitol is chiral.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] A useful English-language mnemonic device is that "threitol" and "chiral" both begin with consonants, whereas "erythritol" and "achiral" both begin with vowels.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Another threo compound is threonine, one of the amino acids coded by DNA.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Its erythro diastereomer, allothreonine, is not coded by DNA and is very rare in nature.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] In alkene addition reactions, syn addition to a trans alkene, or anti addition to a cis alkene, gives a threo product, whereas syn addition to a cis alkene, or anti addition to a trans alkene, gives an erythro product.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] If a molecule contains two asymmetric centers, there are up to four possible configurations, and they cannot all be non-superposable mirror images of each other.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] The possibilities for different isomers continue to multiply as more stereocenters are added to a molecule.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] In general, the number of stereoisomers of a molecule can be determined by calculating 2*n*, where *n* = the number of chiral centers in the molecule.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] This holds true except in cases where the molecule has meso forms.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] These meso compounds are molecules that contain stereocenters, but possess an internal plane of symmetry allowing it to be superposed on its mirror image.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] These equivalent configurations cannot be considered diastereomers.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] For *n* = 3, there are eight stereoisomers.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Among them, there are four pairs of enantiomers: R,R,R and S,S,S; R,R,S and S,S,R; R,S,S and S,R,R; and R,S,R and S,R,S.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] There are many more pairs of diastereomers, because each of these configurations is a diastereomer with respect to every other configuration excluding its own enantiomer (for example, R,R,R is a diastereomer of R,R,S; R,S,R; and R,S,S).
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] For *n* = 4, there are sixteen stereoisomers, or eight pairs of enantiomers.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] The four enantiomeric pairs of aldopentoses and the eight enantiomeric pairs of aldohexoses (subsets of the five- and six-carbon sugars) are examples of sets of compounds that differ in this way.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Double bond isomers are always considered diastereomers, not enantiomers.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Diastereomerism can also occur at a double bond, where the *cis* vs *trans* relative positions of substituents give two non-superposable isomers.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Many conformational isomers are diastereomers as well.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] In the case of diastereomerism occurring at a double bond, E-Z, or entgegen and zusammen (German), is used in notating nomenclature of alkenes.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] As stated previously, two diastereomers will not have identical chemical properties.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] This knowledge is harnessed in chiral synthesis to separate a mixture of enantiomers.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] This is the principle behind chiral resolution.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] After preparing the diastereomers, they are separated by chromatography or recrystallization.
[src:stereochemistry/diastereomer] Note also the example of the stereochemistry of ketonization of enols and enolates.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] In chemistry, an **enantiomer** (/ɪˈnænti.əmər, ɛ-, -oʊ-/ *ih-NAN-tee-ə-mər*), also known as an **optical isomer**, **antipode**, or **optical antipode**, is one of a pair of molecular entities which are mirror images of each other and non-superposable.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Enantiomer molecules are like right and left hands: one cannot be superposed onto the other without first being converted to its mirror image.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] It is solely a relationship of chirality and the permanent three-dimensional relationships among molecules or other chemical structures: no amount of re-orientation of a molecule as a whole or conformational change converts one chemical into its enantiomer.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Chemical structures with chirality rotate plane-polarized light.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] A mixture of equal amounts of each enantiomer, a *racemic mixture* or a *racemate*, does not rotate light.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Stereoisomers include both enantiomers and diastereomers.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Diastereomers, like enantiomers, share the same molecular formula and are also non-superposable onto each other; however, they are not mirror images of each other.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] The R/S system is based on the molecule's geometry with respect to a chiral center.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] The R/S system is assigned to a molecule based on the priority rules assigned by Cahn–Ingold–Prelog priority rules, in which the group or atom with the largest atomic number is assigned the highest priority and the group or atom with the smallest atomic number is assigned the lowest priority.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] The (+) or (−) symbol is used to specify a molecule's optical rotation — the direction in which the polarization of light rotates as it passes through a solution containing the molecule.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] When a molecule is denoted dextrorotatory, it rotates the plane of polarized light clockwise and can also be denoted as (+).
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] When it is denoted as levorotatory, it rotates the plane of polarized light counterclockwise and can also be denoted as (−).
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] The Latin words for *left* are *laevus* and *sinister*, and the word for *right* is *dexter* (or *rectus* in the sense of correct or virtuous).
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] The English word *right* is a cognate of *rectus*.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] This is the origin of the *D*/*L* and *R*/*S* notations and the employment of prefixes *levo-* and *dextro-* in common names.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] The prefix *ar-*, from the Latin *recto* (right), is applied to the right-handed version; *es-*, from the Latin *sinister* (left), to the left-handed molecule.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Example: ketamine, arketamine, esketamine.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] The asymmetric atom is called a **chirality center**, a type of stereocenter.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] A chirality center is also called a *chiral center* or an *asymmetric center*.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Some sources use the terms *stereocenter*, *stereogenic center*, *stereogenic atom* or *stereogen* to refer exclusively to a chirality center, while others use the terms more broadly to refer also to centers that result in diastereomers (stereoisomers that are not enantiomers).
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Compounds that contain exactly one (or any odd number) of asymmetric atoms are always chiral.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] However, compounds that contain an even number of asymmetric atoms sometimes lack chirality because they are arranged in mirror-symmetric pairs, and are known as *meso* compounds.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] For instance, *meso* tartaric acid (shown on the right) has two asymmetric carbon atoms, but it does not exhibit enantiomerism because there is a mirror symmetry plane.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Conversely, there exist forms of chirality that do not require asymmetric atoms, such as axial, planar, and helical chirality.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Even though a chiral molecule lacks reflection (Cs) and rotoreflection symmetries (S2*n*), it can have other molecular symmetries, and its symmetry is described by one of the chiral point groups: C*n*, D*n*, T, O, or I.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] For example, hydrogen peroxide is chiral and has C2 (two-fold rotational) symmetry.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] A common chiral case is the point group C1, meaning no symmetries, which is the case for lactic acid.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] An example of such an enantiomer is the sedative thalidomide, which was sold in a number of countries around the world from 1957 until 1961.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] It was withdrawn from the market when it was found to cause birth defects.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] One enantiomer caused the desirable sedative effects, while the other, unavoidably present in equal quantities, caused birth defects.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] The herbicide mecoprop is a racemic mixture, with the (*R*)-(+)-enantiomer ("Mecoprop-P", "Duplosan KV") possessing the herbicidal activity.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Another example is the antidepressant drugs escitalopram and citalopram.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Citalopram is a racemate [1:1 mixture of (*S*)-citalopram and (*R*)-citalopram]; escitalopram [(*S*)-citalopram] is a pure enantiomer.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] The dosages for escitalopram are typically 1/2 of those for citalopram.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Here, (S)-citalopram is called a chiral switch of Citalopram.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] However, most racemates form crystals containing both enantiomers in a 1:1 ratio.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] In his pioneering work, Louis Pasteur was able to isolate the isomers of sodium ammonium tartrate because the individual enantiomers crystallize separately from solution.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] To be sure, equal amounts of the enantiomorphic crystals are produced, but the two kinds of crystals can be separated with tweezers.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] A less common method is by enantiomer self-disproportionation.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] The second strategy is asymmetric synthesis: the use of various techniques to prepare the desired compound in high enantiomeric excess.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Techniques encompassed include the use of chiral starting materials (chiral pool synthesis), the use of chiral auxiliaries and chiral catalysts, and the application of asymmetric induction.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] The use of enzymes (biocatalysis) may also produce the desired compound.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] A third strategy is enantioconvergent synthesis, the synthesis of one enantiomer from a racemic precursor, utilizing both enantiomers.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] By making use of a chiral catalyst, both enantiomers of the reactant result in a single enantiomer of product.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Enantiomers may not be isolable if there is an accessible pathway for racemization (interconversion between enantiomorphs to yield a racemic mixture) at a given temperature and timescale.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] For example, amines with three distinct substituents are chiral, but with few exceptions (e.g. substituted *N*-chloroaziridines), they rapidly undergo "umbrella inversion" at room temperature, leading to racemization.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] If the racemization is fast enough, the molecule can often be treated as an achiral, averaged structure.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] For all intents and purposes, each enantiomer in a pair has the same energy.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] This difference in energy is far smaller than energy changes caused by even small changes in molecular conformation, and far too small to measure by current technology, and is therefore chemically inconsequential.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] In the sense used by particle physicists, the "true" enantiomer of a molecule, which has exactly the same mass-energy content as the original molecule, is a mirror-image that is also *built from antimatter* (antiprotons, antineutrons, and positrons).
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Throughout this article, "enantiomer" is used only in the chemical sense of compounds of ordinary matter that are not superposable on their mirror image.
[src:stereochemistry/enantiomer] Quasi-enantiomers have applications in parallel kinetic resolution.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] For instance, sucrose and camphor are *d*-rotary whereas cholesterol is *l*-rotary.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] For a given substance, the angle by which the polarization of light of a specified wavelength is rotated is proportional to the path length through the material and (for a solution) proportional to its concentration.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Optical activity is measured using a polarized source and polarimeter.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] This is a tool particularly used in the sugar industry to measure the sugar concentration of syrup, and generally in chemistry to measure the concentration or enantiomeric ratio of chiral molecules in solution.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Modulation of a liquid crystal's optical activity, viewed between two sheet polarizers, is the principle of operation of liquid-crystal displays (used in most modern televisions and computer monitors).
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] A chemical compound that causes dextrorotation is *dextrorotatory* or *dextrorotary*, while a compound that causes laevorotation is *laevorotatory* or *laevorotary*.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Compounds with these properties consist of chiral molecules and are said to have optical activity.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] If a chiral molecule is dextrorotary, its enantiomer (geometric mirror image) will be laevorotary, and vice versa.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Enantiomers rotate plane-polarized light the same number of degrees, but in opposite directions.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] A compound may be labeled as dextrorotary by using the "(+)-" or "*d*-" prefix.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Likewise, a levorotary compound may be labeled using the "(−)-" or "*l*-" prefix.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry, the authority on chemical nomenclature, strongly discourages use of the "*d*-" and "*l*-" prefixes.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The lowercase "*d*-" and "*l*-" prefixes are distinct from the SMALL CAPS "D-" and "L-" prefixes.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The "D-" and "L-" prefixes are used to specify the enantiomer of chiral organic compounds in biochemistry and are based on the compound's absolute configuration relative to (+)-glyceraldehyde, which is the D-form by definition.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The prefix used to indicate absolute configuration is not directly related to the (+) or (−) prefix used to indicate optical rotation in the same molecule.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] For example, nine of the nineteen L-amino acids naturally occurring in proteins are, despite the L- prefix, actually dextrorotary (at a wavelength of 589 nm), and D-fructose is sometimes called "levulose" because it is levorotary.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The two naming systems can be combined to indicate both absolute configuration and optical rotation, as in D-(+)-glyceraldehyde.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The D- and L- prefixes describe the molecule as a whole, as do the (+) and (−) prefixes for optical rotation.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In contrast, the (*R*)- and (*S*)- prefixes from the Cahn–Ingold–Prelog priority rules characterize the absolute configuration of each specific chiral stereocenter with the molecule, rather than a property of the molecule as a whole.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] A molecule having exactly one chiral stereocenter (usually an asymmetric carbon atom) can be labeled (*R*) or (*S*), but a molecule having multiple stereocenters needs more than one label.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] For example, the essential amino acid L-threonine contains two chiral stereocenters and is written (2*S*,3*S*)-threonine.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] There is no strict relationship between the R/S, the D/L, and (+)/(−) designations, although some correlations exist.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] For example, of the naturally occurring amino acids, all are L, and most are (*S*).
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] For some molecules the (*R*)-enantiomer is the dextrorotary (+) enantiomer, and in other cases it is the levorotary (−) enantiomer.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The relationship must be determined on a case-by-case basis with experimental measurements or detailed computer modeling.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The rotation of the orientation of linearly polarized light was first observed in 1811 in quartz by French physicist François Arago.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In 1820, the English astronomer Sir John F.W.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Herschel discovered that different individual quartz crystals, whose crystalline structures are mirror images of each other (see illustration), rotate linear polarization by equal amounts but in opposite directions.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Jean Baptiste Biot also observed the rotation of the axis of polarization in certain liquids and vapors of organic substances such as turpentine.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Simple polarimeters have been used since this time to measure the concentrations of simple sugars, such as glucose, in solution.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In fact one name for D-glucose (the biological isomer), is *dextrose*, referring to the fact that it causes linearly polarized light to rotate to the right or dexter side.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In a similar manner, levulose, more commonly known as fructose, causes the plane of polarization to rotate to the left.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Fructose is even more strongly levorotatory than glucose is dextrorotatory.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Invert sugar syrup, commercially formed by the hydrolysis of sucrose syrup to a mixture of the component simple sugars, fructose, and glucose, gets its name from the fact that the conversion causes the direction of rotation to "invert" from right to left.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In 1849, Louis Pasteur resolved a problem concerning the nature of tartaric acid.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] A solution of this compound derived from living things (to be specific, wine lees) rotates the plane of polarization of light passing through it, but tartaric acid derived by chemical synthesis has no such effect, even though its reactions are identical and its elemental composition is the same.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Pasteur noticed that crystals of this compound come in two asymmetric forms that are mirror images of one another.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Sorting the crystals by hand gave two forms of the compound: Solutions of one form rotate polarized light clockwise, while the other form rotate light counterclockwise.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] An equal mix of the two has no polarizing effect on light.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Pasteur deduced that the molecule in question is asymmetric and could exist in two different forms that resemble one another as would left- and right-hand gloves, and that the organic form of the compound consists of purely the one type.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] If the 4 neighbors are all different, then there are two possible orderings of the neighbors around the tetrahedron, which will be mirror images of each other.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] This led to a better understanding of the three-dimensional nature of molecules.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In 1898, Jagadish Chandra Bose described the ability of twisted artificial structures to rotate the polarization of microwaves.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Lindman showed the same effect for an artificial composite consisting of randomly-dispersed left- or right-handed wire helices in cotton.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Since the early 21st century, the development of artificial materials has led to the prediction and realization of chiral metamaterials with optical activity exceeding that of natural media by orders of magnitude in the optical part of the spectrum.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Extrinsic chirality associated with oblique illumination of metasurfaces lacking two-fold rotational symmetry has been observed to lead to large linear optical activity in transmission and reflection, as well as nonlinear optical activity exceeding that of lithium iodate by 30 million times.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In 1945, Charles William Bunn predicted optical activity of achiral structures, if the wave's propagation direction and the achiral structure form an experimental arrangement that is different from its mirror image.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Such optical activity due to extrinsic chirality was observed in the 1960s in liquid crystals.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In 1950, Sergey Vavilov predicted optical activity that depends on the intensity of light and the effect of nonlinear optical activity was observed in 1979 in lithium iodate crystals.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Optical activity is normally observed for transmitted light.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Silverman discovered that polarization rotation can also occur for light reflected from chiral substances.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Shortly after, it was observed that chiral media can also reflect left-handed and right-handed circularly polarized waves with different efficiencies.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] These phenomena of specular circular birefringence and specular circular dichroism are jointly known as specular optical activity.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Specular optical activity is very weak in natural materials.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Optical activity occurs due to molecules dissolved in a fluid or due to the fluid itself only if the molecules are one of two (or more) stereoisomers; this is known as an enantiomer.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The structure of such a molecule is such that it is *not* identical to its mirror image (which would be that of a different stereoisomer, or the "opposite enantiomer").
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In mathematics, this property is also known as chirality.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] For instance, a metal rod is *not* chiral, since its appearance in a mirror is not distinct from itself.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] However a screw or light bulb base (or any sort of helix) *is* chiral; an ordinary right-handed screw thread, viewed in a mirror, would appear as a left-handed screw (very uncommon) which could not possibly screw into an ordinary (right-handed) nut.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] A human viewed in a mirror would have their heart on the right side, clear evidence of chirality, whereas the mirror reflection of a doll might well be indistinguishable from the doll itself.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In order to display optical activity, a fluid must contain only one, or a preponderance of one, stereoisomer.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] If two enantiomers are present in equal proportions, then their effects cancel out and no optical activity is observed; this is termed a racemic mixture.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] But when there is an enantiomeric excess, more of one enantiomer than the other, the cancellation is incomplete and optical activity is observed.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Many naturally occurring molecules are present as only one enantiomer (such as many sugars).
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Chiral molecules produced within the fields of organic chemistry or inorganic chemistry are racemic unless a chiral reagent was employed in the same reaction.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] At the fundamental level, polarization rotation in an optically active medium is caused by circular birefringence, and can best be understood in that way.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Whereas linear birefringence in a crystal involves a small difference in the phase velocity of light of two different linear polarizations, circular birefringence implies a small difference in the velocities between right and left-handed *circular polarizations*.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Think of one enantiomer in a solution as a large number of little helices (or screws), all right-handed, but in random orientations.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Birefringence of this sort is possible even in a fluid because the handedness of the helices is not dependent on their orientation: even when the direction of one helix is reversed, it still appears right handed.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] And circularly polarized light itself is chiral: as the wave proceeds in one direction the electric (and magnetic) fields composing it are rotating clockwise (or counterclockwise for the opposite circular polarization), tracing out a right (or left) handed screw pattern in space.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Unlike linear birefringence, however, natural optical rotation (in the absence of a magnetic field) cannot be explained in terms of a local material permittivity tensor (i.e., a charge response that only depends on the local electric field vector), as symmetry considerations forbid this.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Rather, circular birefringence only appears when considering nonlocality of the material response, a phenomenon known as spatial dispersion.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Nonlocality means that electric fields in one location of the material drive currents in another location of the material.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Light travels at a finite speed, and even though it is much faster than the electrons, it makes a difference whether the charge response naturally wants to travel along with the electromagnetic wavefront, or opposite to it.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Spatial dispersion means that light travelling in different directions (different wavevectors) sees a slightly different permittivity tensor.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Natural optical rotation requires a special material, but it also relies on the fact that the wavevector of light is nonzero, and a nonzero wavevector bypasses the symmetry restrictions on the local (zero-wavevector) response.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] However, there is still reversal symmetry, which is why the direction of natural optical rotation must be 'reversed' when the direction of the light is reversed, in contrast to magnetic Faraday rotation.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] All optical phenomena have some nonlocality/wavevector influence but it is usually negligible; natural optical rotation, rather uniquely, absolutely requires it.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The phase velocity of light in a medium is commonly expressed using the index of refraction *n*, defined as the speed of light (in free space) divided by its speed in the medium.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] While $\Delta n$ is small in natural materials, examples of giant circular birefringence resulting in a negative refractive index for one circular polarization have been reported for chiral metamaterials.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The familiar rotation of the axis of *linear* polarization relies on the understanding that a linearly polarized wave can as well be described as the superposition (addition) of a left and right circularly polarized wave in equal proportion.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] where $\mathbf {E} _{\theta _{0}}$ is the electric field of the net wave, while $\mathbf {E} _{\text{RHC}}$ and $\mathbf {E} _{\text{LHC}}$ are the two circularly polarized basis functions (having zero phase difference).
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] where ${\hat {x}}$ and ${\hat {y}}$ are unit vectors, and *i* is the imaginary unit, in this case representing the 90-degree phase shift between the *x* and *y* components that we have decomposed each circular polarization into.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] As usual when dealing with phasor notation, it is understood that such quantities are to be multiplied by $e^{-i\omega t}$ and then the actual electric field at any instant is given by the *real part* of that product.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Now let us assume transmission through an optically active material which induces an additional phase difference between the right and left circularly polarized waves of $2\Delta \theta$ .
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Let us call $\mathbf {E} _{\text{out}}$ the result of passing the original wave linearly polarized at angle $\theta$ through this medium.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] We defined above the difference in the refractive indices for right and left circularly polarized waves of $\Delta n$ .
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] where $\lambda$ is the wavelength of the light (in vacuum).
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] This will cause a rotation of the linear axis of polarization by $\Delta \theta$ as we have shown.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In general, the refractive index depends on wavelength (see dispersion) and the differential refractive index $\Delta n$ will also be wavelength dependent.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The resulting variation in rotation with the wavelength of the light is called optical rotatory dispersion (ORD).
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] ORD spectra and circular dichroism spectra are related through the Kramers–Kronig relations.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Complete knowledge of one spectrum allows the calculation of the other.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Although optical activity is normally thought of as a property of fluids, particularly aqueous solutions, it has also been observed in crystals such as quartz (SiO2).
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Although quartz has a substantial linear birefringence, that effect is cancelled when propagation is along the optic axis.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In that case, rotation of the plane of polarization is observed due to the relative rotation between crystal planes, thus making the crystal formally chiral as we have defined it above.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The rotation of the crystal planes can be right or left-handed, again producing opposite optical activities.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] On the other hand, amorphous forms of silica such as fused quartz, like a racemic mixture of chiral molecules, has no net optical activity since one or the other crystal structure does not dominate the substance's internal molecular structure.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] For a pure substance in solution, if the color and path length are fixed and the specific rotation is known, the observed rotation can be used to calculate the concentration.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] This usage makes a polarimeter a tool of great importance to those trading in or using sugar syrups in bulk.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Rotation of light's plane of polarization may also occur through the Faraday effect, which involves a static magnetic field.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] However, this is a distinct phenomenon and is not classified as "optical activity".
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Optical activity is reciprocal, i.e. it is the same for opposite directions of wave propagation through an optically active medium, for example, clockwise polarization rotation from the point of view of an observer.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In case of optically active isotropic media, the rotation is the same for any direction of wave propagation.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] In contrast, the Faraday effect is non-reciprocal, i.e. opposite directions of wave propagation through a Faraday medium will result in clockwise and anti-clockwise polarization rotation from the point of view of an observer.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] Faraday rotation depends on the propagation direction relative to that of the applied magnetic field.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] All compounds can exhibit polarization rotation in the presence of an applied magnetic field, provided that (a component of) the magnetic field is oriented in the direction of light propagation.
[src:stereochemistry/optical-rotation] The Faraday effect is one of the first discoveries of the relationship between light and electromagnetic effects.
